ce:section.ce:para:
In order to explore the source of peroxidase-like activity of CTEzyme, PDs were prepared without Cu-doping, which were unable to catalyze the oxidation of TMB in the presence of H2O2 (Fig. 4e), suggesting doping was a key to regulate the catalytic activity of PDs. In addition, the negligible absorbance was achieved in the presence of Cu2+ ions, indicating that the catalytic activity of CTEzyme was not caused by free Cu2+. Similar results were also achieved for the other two chromogenic substrates (ABTS and OPD) (Fig. 4f, g). Therefore, CTEzyme possessed intrinsic peroxidase-like activity. In addition, the peroxidase-like activity of CTEzyme was also proved by the fluorescence of oxOPD (DAP) at 555 nm (Fig. S7). Furthermore, the steady-state kinetic experiments were performed to quantitatively evaluate the peroxidase-like activity of CTEzyme. Typical Michaelis-Menten curves were obtained by maintaining a constant concentration of CTEzyme while altering the concentrations of TMB and H2O2 (Fig. S8), and Michaelis constant (K

                           m
                        ) values were determined to 0.518 mM for TMB, and 9.052 mM for H2O2.
